\f2\i0 \cf2 Yes, Arabelle was sure that was the half-elf\'92s name. Maybe knowing it would help the captain stop these attacks on people\'92s homes.\
Following the crow, the two women found themselves walking up the hill. It had been a long time since Arabelle was last in Vallaki, and she certainly wouldn\'92t have come to this neighbourhood. \
It had been rare for her family to come to the city. They didn\'92t often need to, and the roads were too dangerous to be worth the trip. Plus, Arabelle was an unruly child. The tears on her clothes and scrapes on her knees were a testament to that. So, it was rarer still for them to bring Arabelle with them. But lately, since 
\f3\i the dream
\f2\i0 , her mum had started treating Arabelle differently, taking her more seriously. So, they went to Vallaki together. Arabelle would never forget that day.\
The first time she saw the market she was flooded by smells, colours and noises. From fresh buttery pastries to musky incense, from dark clothed figures to bright Vistani stalls, from merchants shouting their business to beggars moaning quietly. Her mum had gone to the Vistani, trading rare plants she harvested from the mountains around their farm in Krezk for others you can\'92t find in Barovia. That was when she got Arabelle the amber-encased Nightshade she still wore as a necklace.\
After the market, they had gone to arrange a room at The Blue Water Inn, where they would stay the night before travelling back home the next day. What an exciting night it had turned out to be! Her mum had woken her up in the dead of night and, in a cloak of shadows, they snuck out into the streets to meet a Vistani woman, who led them into her camp. And there\'85 she had met Madame Eva.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl276\slmult1\sa240\qj\partightenfactor0

\f3\i \cf2 \'93We share a gift, little one. It won\'92t always feel like a gift. At times, it might scare you. You might feel lost, and that is because you hold a tether to the lost, and the tether is slight and fragile, a thread that could break from weather or wind or time. \
\'93Your work is to keep growing and bloom in your small bright life. You cannot change the forest even as you see the animals tearing into each other\'92s bodies there. You bring peace to the forest by glowing palely in your beauty.\
\'93Be well, and beware.\'94\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl276\slmult1\sa240\qj\partightenfactor0

\f2\i0 \cf2 Bringing herself back to the present, Arabelle smiled and touched the pouch where she kept her Tarokka deck. That had been the best gift she\'92d gotten that day. \
Looking around, Arabelle noticed that the higher up the hill they walked, the grander the houses looked. So many of them were destroyed or abandoned; some had a silver eye on their front doors, and those looked the least damaged. In the faint, mist-filtered light of the morning, they looked sad and void of life. Peeking from one of the windows, Arabelle saw a pair of mistrustful eyes, following her as she passed.\
\'93Not very friendly, folk up here, are they?\'94 Arabelle asked, as a shiver ran down her spine.\
\'93Would you be?\'94 Magda asked back.\
As Arabelle opened her mouth to respond, Magda cut her off, raising a hand. \'93You\'92re a special case. I honestly don\'92t understand how you\'92re so\'85 cheery. Boravia doesn\'92t exactly encourage solidarity. The Devil seems to enjoy his people\'92s misery, and he knows there is strength in numbers. He can\'92t have that.\'94\
\'93But didn\'92t the people stand together against Fiona Watcher? That\'92s how you won!\'94\
\'93Survival instincts aren\'92t enough to create a community. You can see for yourself. As soon as that threat was over, people found a way of segregating themselves again.\'94\
Still following the crow, Arabelle thought back to Madame Eva\'92s words. 
\f3\i \'93Your work is to keep growing and bloom in your small bright life.\'94 
\f2\i0 But she didn\'92t want her life to be small anymore.\
The crow landed on a streetlamp, flapped his wings, and cawed one last time.\
