\fs22 \cf2 The fire had burned out hours ago, and all that was left was a smouldering blackened wreck, but the smell of smoke clung so thick it could have still been billowing.\
\
Arabelle and Magda picked through the wreckage, daylight streaming through holes in the walls of the burnt-out foundation. \
\
\'93We can\'92t even identify the bodies,\'94 Alek said. He stood near the door like the place was unholy. \'93There were three bodies. Only two people live here, and they don\'92t look like the right sizes. We couldn\'92t\'85\'94 He stopped, sniffing deeply, collecting himself. \'93You can\'92t tell any features from what\'92s left.\'94 He scratched at his five o\'92 clock shadow. They could tell he hadn\'92t slept.\
\
\'93So you\'92ve got an extra person,\'94 Arabelle said.\
\
\'93At least one\'85\'94 Magda said. \'93Is anyone who lived here accounted for?\'94\
\
Alek shook his head. He looked at her like he was turning what she\'92d said over in his head, but before he could say anything, Arabelle chimed in, \'93Well, the third person is probably the one who started the fire, right?\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s our theory anyway,\'94 he said, with a pause. \'93And no. No-one accounted for. But, it\'92s not like we can take a census. There are a lot of people missing at the moment.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s revolution for you,\'94 Magda said. She was squatting by a scorch mark in the centre of the room. \'93The bodies you found. Where were they?\'94\
\
\'93Two on the ground in kitchen, next to each other, and one lying where you\'92re standing, Arabelle. It looked like that one had been trying to get out.\'94\
\
Arabelle shivered, and stepped off where she was standing. \
\
Then she looked down. \'93Oh. You\'92re right.\'94 Once it was pointed out to her, she could see there was an outline on the ground, an inverted snow angel on the floorboards where the person had shielded the floor from the flames with their body.\
\
Magda peeked through to the other room before counting on her fingers. \'93One two three. Hm.\'94 She looked around the room, all business now before she confirmed, \'93This is the building that the fires started in?\'94\
\
Alek cleared his throat. \'93They started in a few places across town, but as far as we can tell, this was one of them.\'94\
\
Magda was still looking around the room. \'93Four,\'94 she said absently, looking up at the wall furthest from them.\
\
\'93What?\'94\
\
\'93One two three four.\'94 She stared at the wall intently.\
\
Alek looked confused.\
\
\'93Oh! You\'92re right, I see it!\'94 Arabelle said. \
\
Magda stood opposite the wall and raised her hands above her head as though she was following instructions.\
\uc0\u8232 \'93No, wait, hang on,\'94 Arabelle said. She rushed behind Magda and tried to adjust her arms into some position, but Magda brushed her away.\
\
\'93Stop that, don\'92t touch me,\'94 she snapped.\
\
\'93Sorry,\'94 Arabelle drew her hands away like she was on fire. Magda brushed her shoulder and went back to what she was doing.\
\
\'93Sorry, what?\'94 Alek raised an eyebrow.\
\
\'93Look,\'94 Arabelle said. She brought Alek back to the very edge of the room by the shattered window pane, and suddenly it came into focus.\
\
The entire back wall of the room had that same scorch mark, blown up to scale. Like someone standing in the center of the room had cast a shadow onto the wall from a bright light.\
\
\'93There was a fourth person in the room. Someone didn\'92t just set the building on fire\'85\'94 Alek said. \'93They blew it up.\'94\
\
\'93Something powerful enough to incinerate a human body on contact,\'94 Magda said. \'93Believe me, I know angry mobs. You don\'92t get that kind of blast with a molotov cocktail. It must have been some kind of bomb, or a--\'94\
\
\'93Or a Fireball spell!\'94 Arabelle said. \'93A powerful one.\'94\
\
\'93You think a mage did this?\'94 Alek scrunched up his face. \'93I mean, it would narrow it down to a handful of people. But who among them would have motive?\'94\
\
\'93Arabelle dear, would you stand where I\'92m standing?\'94 Magda stepped away, and considered the room while Arabelle got into position. \'93What\'92s the range on a Fireball? One hundred and twenty feet?\'94\
\
\'93Hundred and fifty,\'94 Arabelle corrected.\
\
Magda stepped out of the front door, looking at the ground and counting her steps. At a hundred paces she stepped into view on the other side of the window, standing in the middle of the street. She raised a hand like a gun, closing one eye for line of sight down her finger and pointing it at Arabelle. \'93Looks about right.\'94\
\
Arabelle mimed being blown up in slow motion, flailing her arms slowly and making explosion sound effects.\
\
Alek coughed. \'93Arabelle, I knew these people well.\'94\
\
She cringed. \'93Sorry.\'94\
\
Magda stepped in. \'93I think we have your story.\'94\
\
Alek lit a cigar, giving himself a second to think about it while he looked around the room. The picture was coming together clearly now.\
